04695nam a22006975i 9780824864637DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20082008hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248646377 a10.1515/97808248646372doi  a(DE-B1597)484398  a(OCoLC)1024009086  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBJ117 -- R67 2009eb 7aREL0180002bisacsh04a173.09511 aRosemont, Henry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Chinese Classic of Family Reverence :bA Philosophical Translation of the Xiaojing /cHenry Rosemont, Roger T. Ames. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (152 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tTranslators’ Preface -- tIntroduction -- tClassic of Family Reverence (Xiaojing) -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFew if any philosophical schools have championed family values as persistently as the early Confucians, and a great deal can be learned by attending to what they had to say on the subject. In the Confucian tradition, human morality and the personal realization it inspires are grounded in the cultivation of family feeling. One may even go so far as to say that, for China, family reverence was a necessary condition for developing any of the other human qualities of excellence. On the basis of the present translation of the Xiaojing (Classic of Family Reverence) and supplemental passages found in other early philosophical writings, Professors Rosemont and Ames articulate a specifically Confucian conception of "role ethics" that, in its emphasis on a relational conception of the person, is markedly different from most early and contemporary dominant Western moral theories. This Confucian role ethics takes as its inspiration the perceived necessity of family feeling as the entry point in the development of moral competence and as a guide to the religious life as well.In the lengthy introduction, two senior scholars offer their perspective on the historical, philosophical, and religious dimensions of the Xiaojing. Together with this introduction, a lexicon of key terms presents a context for the Xiaojing and provides guidelines for interpreting the text historically in China as well as suggesting its contemporary significance for all societies. The inclusion of the Chinese text adds yet another dimension to this important study. The Chinese Classic of Family Reverence is sure to appeal to specialists of comparative and Chinese philosophy and to all readers interested in the enduring importance of the family.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aRELIGION / Confucianism.2bisacsh1 aAmes, Roger T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486463740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824864637423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824864637.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSH